{"cursor":"10306","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Stark}} {{infobox book | \n| name = Stark title_orig = translator = image = caption = First edition\n| cover author = Ben Elton illustrator = cover_artist = David Scutt country\n| = United Kingdom language = English series = genre = Dystopian fiction,\n| Environmental Fiction publisher = Sphere Books release_date = January 1,\n| 1989 english_release_date = media_type = Print pages = 496 isbn = ISBN\n| 0-7474-0390-2\n}} 'Stark' is a 1989 novel by comedian Ben Elton. It was commercially and\ncritically successful in the United Kingdom and Australia. It was Elton's first\nnovel, and launched his writing career. Stark was reprinted 23 times in its\nfirst year, and ultimately sold well over a million copies, making Elton one of\na small number of novelists to sell more than a million copies of his or her\nfirst book. Ben Elton, Stark (Black Swan edition, 2006), Copyright\nnotice. Gilchrist, Jim:\n[http://living.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1065852007 Doyle variety performance],\n[[The Scotsman]], 9 July 2007 The novel was adapted into [[Stark (TV\nminiseries)|Stark]], a television miniseries.\n\nIt is a comedy with environmental themes. The comedy style has been compared\nwith the literary works of Douglas Adams and Grant\nNaylor. [http://www.illiterarty.com/reviews/stark Illiterarty] It\nis set mainly in Australia, in a dystopian near-future, and the lead\nprotagonist is an expat Englishman. The story is told from the point of view\nof a large number of characters, and the point of view often temporarily\nshifts to that of an animal. Much of the early plot takes place in Carlton, a\nfictional town south of Perth, Western Australia. Most of the rest of the\nnovel takes place in Kalgoorkatta and Bullens Creek, in the Western\nAustralian desert. The final scene takes place at an unspecified location in\nouter space, perhaps on the Moon.\n","linknr":220,"url":"Stark_(novel)","recorded":1364153648,"links":["/w